{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T16-29-00-131Z","slug":"docker-makes-everything-better","locale":"fr","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T16:29:05.604Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2015-03-12--docker-makes-everything-better/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2015-03-12--docker-makes-everything-better/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/docker-makes-everything-better/fr/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T16-29-00-131Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"08d486f9c2de30d5fb48366896dd7b510ef52ed6828cfc4bee83cc6e66923885","outputHash":"daa3390f9b4cedfed98b96ddbf857f4d9d9a0c6647632b34864acfea47b6e628","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article “Docker === Love” is a 2015‑style tutorial aimed at developers and DevOps newcomers who want to use Docker for local development and testing. Its core thesis is that Docker lets you experiment with tools, servers, and your own software in isolated containers, dramatically reducing the risk of contaminating the host system and encouraging more modular, idempotent code. The piece walks through basic Docker concepts (the meaning of `-it` vs. `-d`) and provides concrete `docker run` examples for nginx and Node.js, emphasizing shared‑folder mounts and port mapping. The tone is upbeat and encouraging, treating Docker as a “time‑capsule” of early enthusiasm while warning readers to modernize the security practices before using it in production. Recurring metaphors frame Docker as a “sandbox” that protects the host and a “love‑letter” to containerization, reinforcing the idea that Docker simplifies the entire software development lifecycle.","totalInputTokens":2024,"totalOutputTokens":568,"totalCacheReadTokens":1024,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":4099,"totalCostUsd":0.00018117600000000001,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"open